content: Stream created by Grahame Grieve.
ok. so I'm properly into my holiday around Australia. So far, I've done 4000km in my 4wd, and I'm nearly as far north as you can drive along the east coast of Australia, in the Daintree rainforest.

sunrise over nsw on the first day.

image.png https://scontent.fbne5-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.6435-9/204288925_10158063929897124_8845412330523442179_n.jpg?_nc_cat=103&ccb=1-3&_nc_sid=8bfeb9&_nc_ohc=PdstDMiZZhQAX9PLXhZ&_nc_ht=scontent.fbne5-1.fna&oh=3e3b5efa69a5ebbec8a297af575bade9&oe=60E9F01D
I had to traverse NSW with only one stop for fuel - 12.5 hours of driving. (Covid related rules)
Day 3 was a wipe out: my camper trail axle broke:

Day 4: Back on the road, and totally boring. The most interesting thing was stopping for fuel at a place called "Banana"

image.pnghttps://scontent.fbne5-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.6435-9/208962708_10158067556557124_8033394275458174598_n.jpg?_nc_cat=102&ccb=1-3&_nc_sid=8bfeb9&_nc_ohc=DLhNZeHgPbgAX9x94Y7&_nc_ht=scontent.fbne5-1.fna&oh=e74cfacfd3be8914a1be8d6960cb6c83&oe=60E9D1DC
Day 5: Drove to Mackay. The other wheel nearly broke; a mechanic gave it a very thorough fix indeed. No photos
Day 6: chilled in Mackay. It's sugar cane country, and has special sugar cane trains.
Also, the traffic lights in Mackay need to grow up
Day 7: hiking in rainforest behind Mackay; no photos, since my camera was unexpectedly flat. But I did get a video of a water crossing:

Day 8: went an a cruise out to the coral reef: image.png https://scontent.fbne5-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.6435-9/208984571_10158074706207124_5813770740974511827_n.jpg?_nc_cat=102&ccb=1-3&_nc_sid=8bfeb9&_nc_ohc=6UQqZ8BAqsMAX8nhUzU&_nc_ht=scontent.fbne5-1.fna&oh=00d678ad416b631a519927fcaf2890ff&oe=60E92977
Day 9: Mackay to Cairns - whole day on the road, nothing interesting at all about it. Picked up Kath who flew in at the end of the day

Day 10: Drove up to Daintree forest national park. Sunset over Daintree river: image.png https://scontent.fbne5-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.6435-9/211449349_10224583281784867_8200085301007886830_n.jpg?_nc_cat=102&ccb=1-3&_nc_sid=8bfeb9&_nc_ohc=cmhDe78n4R8AX9pw9Bu&_nc_ht=scontent.fbne5-1.fna&oh=004b7b1f9dec2ddbbc9230fa505ee3bd&oe=60E8D6DB

Day 11: exploring the daintree - tropical rainforest in the far north of queensland.

sorry for the long silence. Bandwith is even less available out here in outback Australia than I realised. And my iPhone sure doesn't like being offline...
palms in daintree rainforest - wet and steamy (and rained continuously)
Mossman gorge, south from Daintree. Too rapid to swim in

later that same day, cloudless sky, setting up camp with some friends who are travelling with us for a couple of weeks.
looking down into Cobbold Gorge in central Queensland. Temperature from hereafter is 30C+
Is it only the iPhone that struggles with being offline? :wink: Looks amazing!
Well, I’m at “Hell’s Gate” one of the most desolate places in Australia. Photo out of order since I have a little bandwidth
Loving these photos. I recall trying to swim in Mossman Gorge back in 1990 and how strong the current was.

Some day, I'll get enough bandwidth to catch up with some photos. I'm now in Borroloola after 400km of tough road, with no coverage anywhere, and camping overnight. Quite a bit of the trip was 40km max due to how hard the road was. Only broke a few things on the 4wd and camper trailer (had to replace the screws on the fridge tray after the broke).

Anyway, here's a photo of Australian National Highway 1, reduced to a single lane dirt road though private property (elsewhere, it's the main highway around the Australian coast, often a 2x2 lane divided road. But not out here). No bridges either, water crossings - you really need a high clearance 4wd with a snorkel to be confident out here.

Mossman gorge, south from Daintree. Too rapid to swim in

Used to swim there all the time as a kid :). The problem is that when there’s heavy rain on the mountain you can get a wall of water coming down really, really quickly. The local indigenous tribe has cultural sensitivities about drownings in the river, so they now err on the side of caution.

Well, I'm finally back on line with enough bandwidth to run Zulip. (Central / Northern Australia seems to have extensive 4G coverage, but the backbone bandwidth is desparately short, and getting web pages up takes minutes)
so. let's see, it's been a bit dramatic. I last posted from Kakadu, when we arrived.
Mamukala wetlands - a corner of the massive billabong that's the heart of Kakadu

Saltie Crocodile in a billabong on the kakadu backroad (hard core 4wd track)
image.png https://scontent.fadl4-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.6435-9/217520462_10224728384452343_584776619457732213_n.jpg?_nc_cat=101&ccb=1-3&_nc_sid=8bfeb9&_nc_ohc=o2-HAkOKuqAAX_qvwI4&tn=DaNA9FtBsMcfYrqs&_nc_ht=scontent.fadl4-1.fna&oh=a28cff2ece010aab19f2c51b809465e8&oe=612E7926
Next day: we visited Maguk, one of my favourite swimming places in the whole world
next: big croc in the water beside our tour boat on the billabong
a Jabiru hunting, with a crocodile in the background:
Next day, we left Kakadu and went back to Katherine, getting ready to head to our real destination, the Gibb River Road
Katherine was a rest day, fixing a long list of small issues with the van, and preparing for Gibb River Road. Only, I found this:

That's the main strut under the camper trailer, snapped in half. That's a fatal injury to the camper, and really, it would be irresponsible to drive it any more. And also the likely source of a series of problems that I've had with things not lining up. So in one day, three things happened:

  1. The camper trailer died, and was written off by the insurance company. So we would have to retool our camping altogether if we wanted to go on. Probably not a really good idea to do in a day or two on the road
  2. We discovered that although we had official approval to enter western Australia under Covid rules, in actual fact, police turn away >50% of campers at the border (after a 6 hour drive through the desert). Once turned away, forget trying to enter. There is no known rhyme or reason for their decision making (see e.g. https://www.abc.net.au/news/2021-07-08/wa-border-g2g-pass-frustration/100275018)
  3. totally to our surprise, the Northern Territory, the state we're already in, opened to travellers from Victoria, which meant that our daughters could join us. we had planned for them to join us and do the Gibb River Road with us, but there's no chance at all that they'll be allowed into Western Australia (Western Australia is kind of like a fortress right now - hard borders and a big middle finger to the rest of Australia)

So we rejigged our plans, and decided to a road holiday in the Northern Territory with our daughters for a week instead.
The next day, we explored Katherine Gorge:
hot water Springs in Katherine (talking about our plans with friends who had travelled with us for a couple of weeks):
Drove up to Darwin to meet our girls, and caught the sunset over Darwin Harbour
Next day, chilling at the downtown beach with our girls
yes, that's a fake beach. there's a massive concrete wall separating that beach from the crocodiles in the harbour.
Chilling on the back after visiting Mindil Market later that day
Next day, fishing in the Darwin Harbour
we had fish we caught for lunch:
Wangi falls - can't swim here this year, a Saltie crept through their defenses
at the end of a long 4wd track (really 4wd, with snorkel), we found this lovely spot, Surprise Creek Falls

What's a saltie?

A salt water crocodile, though techically they're called Estuarine Crocodiles. Super dangerous predator found throughout warm water in northern Australia
and yes, you can jump into the water here, but I'm not going to try posting videos here - network is not that good
Which brings us to today, back to Kakadu with our girls, and back at the billabong
I did a crocodile cruise on East Alligator river (it's full or crocodiles not alligators, but it was named in early 1800s before that was known)
Wait ... - Is that a FHIR extinguisher (only used when on holiday)?
ok. yesterday, we went back to Maguk, my favourite spot in the Northern Territory
Then a sunset cruise on the billabong again
also, we went down to Jim Jim falls
Today: back to Katherine, visited Edith Falls.

note: these last few days have been covering the same ground as earlier, but this time with our daughters. Kath and the girls have one more day here in Northern Territory, and then they're flying home to lockdown the day after. And then I begin the long slow trip home (3500km drive). Note: I'll be home a week earlier than anticipated after the problems with the camper and the borders
The next day, last with my family, we visited Bitter Springs at Mataranka, a lovely hot water spring.
that afternoon, I went canoeing in the Katherine Gorge with my younger daughter

image.png https://scontent.fbne8-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.6435-9/231548013_10224805064089286_1960990327462099945_n.jpg?_nc_cat=103&ccb=1-4&_nc_sid=8bfeb9&_nc_ohc=evrCK-AR_U0AX8ygTeg&_nc_ht=scontent.fbne8-1.fna&oh=bde834e2745bfe2e3382544487e354d8&oe=61389FF0

That, btw, is a fresh water crocodile - totally harmless
Then in the evening, we went to the Katherine Speedway and watched the races
We didn't get a photo, but two the junior racers rolled their cars - total write off. At least the kids were OK.
The next day, we drove to Darwin (350km) so the rest of my family could get a plane home
Now it's just me, driving home (into lockdown)
packing all the stuff from the written off camper into my car (very full now)
for the trip home, I'm free camping - just camping beside the road in rest areas, No cost, no services.
So far, I've done 1200km. And the view from the road is pretty much this:
but the night sky is pretty amazing out here at night. Here's the iPhone's best effort at taking it, falling far short of reality

Today: swiming in Ellery's creek. Lasted all of sixty seconds; that water is cold

image.png https://scontent.fbne8-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.6435-9/230550754_10158140831252124_682085688022908448_n.jpg?_nc_cat=108&ccb=1-4&_nc_sid=8bfeb9&_nc_ohc=1mC9GvixMj0AX9YFSDd&_nc_ht=scontent.fbne8-1.fna&oh=d2e7ba1e84636b547f911a7c3f314e4e&oe=613AE782
Sleeping on the side of the road has its challenges. I took this video at 3am
the real action starts at 30secs, make sure you have the sound turned up
Yes, he deliberately blew his horn to wake the 200 people or so sleeping on the side of the road. About 1 in 10 trucks did that.
surely he was being kind, warning anyone wandering in the road... people who couldn't hear his truck bearing down on them. :-)
those massive trucks, 3 to 4 trailers on them, up to 60 yards long (called road trains), you can hear them coming for about five minutes.

Regarding freshwater crocodiles, the larger ones (they grow to ~2m) can be aggressive and dangerous during nesting season in ~Sept. We were always warned away from known nesting sites as kids. Not “kill you” dangerous, but will cut you up.
Today, I'm in Oodnadatta, a semi-famous outback destination, still on my way home to Melbourne.
As you can see, I've left the Savannah behind, and I'm in the desert now. (on the edge of the Simpson desert)
The Adventures of Grahame - King of the Desert.
My kids have watched too many episodes of Australia's Deadliest for me to not squirm looking at that open-ended tent...
it has a fly screen on it when I zip it up.
Went to Dalhousie Springs today - a warm spring in the Simpson desert
there was a station (= sheep / cattle farm) out here in 19C but it failed

100m size pool, beautiful warm water - 37C. Outside was a cool 20C with a brisk wind blowing, so it just perfect. (20C feels cold after beingi n the tropics for a few weeks; it's getting colder as a head south, 4C overnight tonight, which is a shock, but I'll be wrapped up warm in my swag and I'm using my SoloStove for heating and cooking (https://www.solostove.com):
The next day, I did the rest of the Oodnadatta track. Sometimes, it looks really like the surface of Mars
It follows the line of the old Ghan, the original north/south railway through central Australia. This is the biggest bridge that still exists from the old Ghan:
Found this on the side of the road in the middle of the desert:
Yes, by normal standards, that's extremely expensive, but it is the middle of an extreme desert
Down the road, i checked out Coward Springs Spa:
It's about 28C, in the middle of the desert. Pretty cool, really, though it would be pretty meh anywhere else
Then passed South Lake Eyre image.png - it's empty right now, probably will be for years (last filled a couple of years ago)
left the desert and crossed back home into Victoria.
First running water I saw since Katherine - 2800km through the middle of Australia, no running rivers
A quick run through Victoria, and I'm finally home:
And now, I'm going to catch up with Zulip (6529 messages)
and here ends this stream, for now.
